snippet.textDisplay:
Everyone saying they should just cancel all cruises doesn't really understand so I'll try and make it simple. That's the same as determining 'alright the economy's done for anyway so let's try this.' And don't tell me not to worry about the economy. Once they do this with cruise lines it won't stop, the problems continue all over. You'd have to add airports and bus tour companies. And why not add hotels onto the list especially ones mainly servicing foreigners since they won't be getting any business once we shut down airports and stop having flights go... I could go on and on about how much stuff they should be shutting down right now to curb the spread. Concerts, sports games, anywhere that big crowds gather- And yet, that would put millions of people out of jobs and collapse the world. Many people don't have huge stores of supplies in their houses, and if everything starts shutting down the government can't just hand a bunch of money to people for them to stay home, that's not how money works. People won't be able to buy their food before long if the 100k people who work on cruises and advertise cruises and all the pilots and flight attendants and TSA and tour guides and coach bus drivers and... and when millions of people are out of work, all they have to do is worry about the virus and panic and read conspiracy theories and come to conclusions that the government isn't doing enough or that maybe the government spread the virus in the first place! Because that's what some people online told them. And so panic rises more. People get racist towards foreigners who can't get home because of the lack of transportation. People start to hoard food and medicine, and when it happens everywhere all at once, there aren't enough excess truck drivers to suddenly meet the new demand so places start to empty out. Now we've got people stuck at home, quarantining themselves in fear of a virus and low on money and on trust of money. Trust of the government systems that we believe got us into this mess.


What I'm trying to articulate, is that unless things are BAD already, the best thing to do is carry on as usual. The people in charge know of all these possibilities and all the negative results that would come from changing the daily routine of the average person, because it would mean admitting the disease's spread is out of hand. Their goal is to allow us to continue living on as usual, because if they can do that then they can convince most people that the disease won't affect them personally. Once tens of thousands of people have to return home or go looking for jobs because they can't just spend months out of work because their cruise line can't function for an undisclosed amount of time which could be indefinite, and those people treat it as a huge deal because it IS a huge deal to them as it's massively impacted their lives at this point, and the other people who hear them treating it as the most important thing going on start freaking out about it causing local authorities to put in measures of their own which freaks out even more people now that the government is worrying about it- It's chaos. It will be chaos. Now, it will also be chaos if the disease starts spreading, but at least that's a controlled chaos. Because people would be too afraid to gather together to protest the government when gathering means risking infection. Anyone hear about protests in Hong Kong recently? Not as much as we were hearing about them before this happened. Why? Because as much as they cared about their rights being trampled upon or about protesting communism and whatnot, dying from a horrible disease is enough of a deterrent that it disincentives public gatherings. It gives the government more control to only react once the terrible things start happening. People may say that the government acted too late, but that's a problem they'd only have to worry about if we all survive which if it got to that point that we have to start quarantining places around America, the concern over the virus will be higher than on the hysteria. Currently though, it's the hysteria which is the most dangerous thing for the US. Because the more we panic about it, the worse things get even if there still hasn't been real community spread here in the states. Even without any cases, there were riots in Ukraine a couple days ago as the expats from Wuhan returned, none of them sick, but going to a government facility for quarantine too close to a town where the people were outraged and did not want them back. In Alabama and California today, local authorities have taken it upon themselves to defy the federal government and say that they won't let back sick passengers from the Diamond Princess. Their people are riled up and they have to act to block it, which means the media has been doing a piss poor job of reassuring the public.


Anyway, moral of the story is to stop saying stupid stuff in the comments like you're a genius and the government leaders are imbeciles for not thinking of shutting down cruises already. Yes they've considered it. They've considered literally everything you can come up with. They have panels of people who spent their lives planning for this and specifically this, and who are sitting around a table right now with a dozen maps around them and looking at data constantly changing their responses based on how best to react to this pandemic. They've had weeks and months to prepare for this in the states while adjusting based on the changes to what we know about the disease, and I am sure they're on top of this. Not only are they on top of it but they've thought of everything I wrote above AND a thousand other things I left out or didn't think of but that they spent years and years coming up with counters for, so it won't even matter because it won't come to be a problem in the first place with those masterminds protecting us. They're like super heroes preventing the world from falling apart right now. Real life super heroes who we will never know as stupid politicians will take the credit for stopping the disease they had nothing to do with except to hopefully agree with those smartest people in this situation and to order other people to carry out the plans of our heroes. If you want to stay inside forever it's your choice to not take cruises anymore, but there're risks in every activity you do. This COVID isn't going to stop, ever. It's not going to die out, it's going to continue on and might be a part of our world now. Once you've accepted that, it's not so scary anymore. Not nearly as much as the potential for chaos should we submit to our fears and join the mob buying in to the hysteria.

snippet.textDisplay:
Are all these numbers of confirmed cases each country posts trustworthy?
Outside the cruise ship, Japan confirmed 132 cases but only tested 693 people. Japan didn't even test the doctors who were in contact with people on the cruise ship and it is speculated they want to avoid confirmed cases being increased by not testing the infected. This is due to the fact that the majority of people, especially young and healthy, will only experience little symptoms and recover without even noticing they were infected. There was one more person from the cruise ship who died but Japan only confirmed that that person died from pneumonia and they are refusing to confirm whether or not that person died from Coronavirus. Their excuse is because the deceased person's family didn't agree to reveal the cause.  South Korea confirmed 602 cases out of 20000; they are currently testing thousands of cases each day.
